Text.Value: You complain a lot.
To live like you, I could learn to be ugly.
Hmph. When the horned ones leave this place, I will lie in the back, and you will pull. Noble one.
I have no more to say. Even old hay tastes better than your idle chatter.
They become birds, to hunt on the wing. Bears, to tear flesh with teeth. But for me - only oxen. Only same old hay.
You'll never be like me.
Another one. What are you under there, then? Ant? Aurochs?
It is not the form - it is the freedom. Your kind walk free, and other beasts carry your burdens.
No - I will be better. I have studied the keepers here.
Your kind give us your burdens. But who will carry ours?
Cheer up - you do a noble thing, carrying burdens for those who can't.
Ant? Are you calling me small?
Maybe you could learn to change as we druids do.
Meditation - a lot of it.
Sometimes I eat the shiny bits, and they have to go looking for them on the other end.
Leave.
The keepers of this place. They change their form to fit their need.
Perhaps we are the true keepers. I will learn to walk on two legs, friend. Then perhaps I will teach them.
One day, I will stride as you do. And perhaps you will carry my burdens.
Surely you could pick a better form than mine.
*Low!*
You mean when the keepers stand and sleep, all at once? My kind learned to do this long ago.
'Shiny bits'? The tieflings put something in your hay?
What are you talking about?
Aurochs describes me well, yes.
Yes. Yes. I would change into a two-legs like you. But how?
And I cannot even eat it, because the horned ones hide their shiny bits inside.
Hiding things, thinking they are clever. Not clever.
Big, and slow? The keepers of this place choose different forms. Better ones.
Maybe I'm an ox too.
If you do not like your form, then choose another. That is what the keepers of this place do.
Hmmm - away. I dream of two-legs. Hmmmmmmmm.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Subtle head lift "over there" type gesture with Ox's head. to dismiss or gesture to player

Text.Value: You have the smell - but I do not think so. You are not like the keepers here.

Synopsis:
The ox is waiting in the cave while the tieflings decide whether to return to the road or not. He has been watching the druids in the grove below, and how they can change into any form they wish. He's wistful and sulky, wishing he could change his own shape from an ox to something less subservient.

He can give us a hint about an item stashed in his hay.
